<subSubSection lastPageId="122" lastPageNumber="123" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="121.[151,1436,1651,2036]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1688,1712]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">Remarks.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[380,478,1687,1711]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">holotype</typeStatus>
female was described with dark brown elytra and an orange pronotum with dark marginal markings. There are several examples herein where different species have marginal dark markings on the pronotum (e.g. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Olivier. McDermott" authorityYear="1966" box="[324,502,1760,1784]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anthracina">
<emphasis box="[324,502,1760,1784]" italics="true" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">Aus. anthracina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ballantyne &amp; Lambkin" authorityYear="2013" baseAuthorityName="Ballantyne &amp; Lambkin" baseAuthorityYear="2013" box="[517,653,1760,1784]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Medeopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulminea">
<emphasis box="[517,653,1760,1784]" italics="true" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">M. fulminea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Olivier. Ballantyne &amp; McLean" authorityYear="1970" box="[667,783,1760,1784]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pupilla">
<emphasis box="[667,783,1760,1784]" italics="true" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">M. pupilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Ballantyne &amp; Lambkin, 2013" authorityName="Ballantyne &amp; Lambkin" authorityYear="2013" box="[798,929,1760,1784]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Trisinuata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicula" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[798,929,1760,1784]" italics="true" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">Tri. apicula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[936,1023,1759,1784]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[936,1019,1760,1784]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
). No males from the type locality of the Bertrand Islands have been located.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="121.[151,1436,1651,2036]" lastBlockId="122.[151,1436,151,284]" lastPageId="122" lastPageNumber="123" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne, L. A. &amp; McLean, M. R." box="[199,614,1831,1855]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" pagination="223 - 305" refId="ref122809" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. &amp; McLean, M. R. (1970) Revisional studies on the firefly genus Pteroptyx Olivier (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae: Luciolini). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 96, 223 - 305." type="journal article" year="1970">Ballantyne and McLean (1970:267)</bibRefCitation>
described as &quot;Species D&quot; 
<specimenCount box="[934,1053,1831,1855]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" type="male">two males</specimenCount>
where the pronotal colour most closely approached that of the 
<typeStatus box="[500,598,1868,1892]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[637,788,1868,1892]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melancholica">
<emphasis box="[637,788,1868,1892]" italics="true" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">melancholica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. While they described the LOs as “filling sternites 6 and 7” their diagrams (
<figureCitation box="[360,475,1903,1927]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="32.[151,250,1897,1920]" captionTargetBox="[176,1416,446,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-160@32.[164,1424,437,1861]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 8. Majority rule tree for larvae analysis. Tree shows the consensus of 4 MPTs of length 2245 from phylogenetic analysis of all characters for the 42 taxa scored for larval characters. New genera, new species, and still undescribed species in red. Showing the % of MPT over 50 %, above branches." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265358" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265358/files/figure.png" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">Fig. 8 n, o</figureCitation>
) indicate a situation where interpretation of the nature of the LO in V7 as either entire or bipartite is not clear, and no further action on these 
<specimenCount box="[765,932,1940,1964]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
is taken here. They also included specimens in 
<taxonomicName authority="Groups" authorityName="Groups" box="[180,493,1975,2000]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Pteroptyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cribellata">
<emphasis box="[180,404,1976,2000]" italics="true" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">Pteroptyx cribellata</emphasis>
Groups
</taxonomicName>
3 and 4 (page 247) where the male pronota had dark markings along the lateral and anterior margins, and in one case also along the posterior margin. All these specimens in Groups 3 and 4 have entire LOs in V7. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne, L. A." box="[374,644,151,175]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" pagination="117 - 170" refId="ref122195" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. (1987 a) Further Revisional Studies on the firefly genus Pteroptyx Olivier (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 113, 117 - 170." type="journal article" year="1987">Ballantyne (1987a:163)</bibRefCitation>
included 
<specimenCount box="[764,905,151,175]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" type="female">two females</specimenCount>
as possible 
<taxonomicName box="[1057,1208,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melancholica">
<emphasis box="[1057,1208,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">melancholica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and indicated that certain 
<taxonomicName box="[235,343,189,212]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Pteroptyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[235,343,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">Pteroptyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(now 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ballantyne &amp; Lambkin" authorityYear="2013" box="[417,563,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Medeopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[417,563,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">Medeopteryx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ballantyne &amp; Lambkin" authorityYear="2013" baseAuthorityName="Ballantyne &amp; Lambkin" baseAuthorityYear="2013" box="[581,679,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Medeopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulminea">
<emphasis box="[581,679,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">fulminea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have lateral pronotal margins finely dark. Certain specimens from Mt Lamington tentatively assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Olivier. McDermott" authorityYear="1966" box="[578,757,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anthracina">
<emphasis box="[578,757,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">Aus. anthracina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have either dark margined or completely pale pronota in the males.
</paragraph>
